Rating: 4
I love this panna cotta recipe and have made it several times. Sometimes, I put caramelized sugar on the bottom of the ramekin before adding the custard -- in imitation of Craig Stolls at Delfina. Pretty and yummy.

Rating: 4
This turned out perfectly: creamy but not too heavy, with just the right sweetness. I followed the recipe exactly, except I didn't dip the ramekins in hot water but only ran the knife around the edges; they released perfectly. I served it with rhubarb-strawberry compote. An easy but impressive dessert for dinner parties!

Rating: 3
I thought this turned out really well considering what minimal effort is required. I served it with sliced blood oranges, which went very well. I was scared that it would be too sweet, but it was just the right amount of sweetness. I felt that the shape collapsed a little too, and would be tempted to add a touch more gelatin next time I make them. Have a photo of it here http://novaclutch.typepad.com/novaclutch/2007/03/buttermilk_pann.html

Rating: 3
So easy and fast, any tart fruit is a nice accompaniment to the smooth sweet custard. Don't leave the ramekins in hot water too long or else it will melt the custard more than necessary to turn it out.

